definition.value: A triol that is butane carrying three hydroxy substituents at position 1, 2 and 3.
A magnesium salt composed of magnesium and dibasic citrate ions in a 1:1 ratio.
An oxime O-ether that is isovaleric acid in which both of the methylene hydrogens at position 2 have been replaced by a methoxyimino group.
A magnesium salt composed of magnesium and citrate ions in a 3:2 ratio.
A 3-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is 2,2-dimethylbutyric acid carrying a single hydroxy substituent at position 3.
A cinnamate ester that is the methyl ester of (E)-3-hydroxycinnamic acid
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of magnesium dichloride.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of manganese(II) chloride.

A hydroxy fatty amide ascaroside obtained by obtained by formal condensation of the 24-hydroxy group of (2E,24R)-24-hydroxy-N-(2-hydroxyethyl)-2-methylpentacos-2-enamide with ascarylopyranose (the alpha anomer). It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
A alicyclic compound that is 3,3-dimethylcyclohex-1-ene carrying a single hydroxy group at position 1.
A cyclopropane substituted at positions 1 and 2 by methylene and acetyl groups respectively.
A pentol consisting of 1-iminohexane with four hydroxy substituents placed at positions 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6.

A glycoside resulting from the reaction of the alcoholic hydroxy group of any hydroxy fatty amide with alpha-ascarylopyranose or its derivatives. They function as semiochemicals in the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
A disaccharide formed by a (1<->1)-glycosidic bond between two hexopyranose units.
Any pentose that exists in the pyranose form.

An (omega-1)-hydroxy fatty acid ascaroside obtained by obtained by formal condensation of the alcoholic hydroxy group of (2E,24R)-2-methylpentacos-2-enoic acid with ascarylopyranose (the alpha anomer). It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
A butenolide that is 3,4-dihydroxyoxolan-2-one carrying an additional 2-hydroxyethanimidoyl substituent at position 5.

An (omega-1)-hydroxy fatty acid ascaroside obtained by obtained by formal condensation of the alcoholic hydroxy group of (24R)-2-methylpentacosanoic acid with ascarylopyranose (the alpha anomer). It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
A pentol consisting of 1-(hydroxyimino)hexane with five hydroxy substituents placed at positions 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6.

A hydroxy fatty amide ascaroside obtained by obtained by formal condensation of the 24-hydroxy group of (24R)-24-hydroxy-N-(2-hydroxyethyl)-2-methyl-3-oxopentacosanamide with ascarylopyranose (the alpha anomer). It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
An aldoxime obtained by formal condensation of glyoxal with two molar equivalents of hydroxylamine.

A hydroxy fatty amide ascaroside obtained by obtained by formal condensation of the 26-hydroxy group of (26R)-26-hydroxy-N-(2-hydroxyethyl)-3-oxoheptacosanamide with ascarylopyranose (the alpha anomer). It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.
A hexadecanoate ester in which the carboxy hydrogen of hexadecanoic acid has been replaced by a tert-butyl group.
A methyl-branched fatty acid that is pentadecanoic acid substituted by a methyl group at position 12.
A methyl ester derived from cyclopropanecarboxylic acid.
A tetrol that is N-(1-iminohexan-2-yl)acetamide in which the four hydroxy substituents are located at positions 3, 4, 5 and 6.
A methyl-branched fatty acid that is pentadecanoic acid substituted by a methyl group at position 13.
An oxime O-ether obtained by formal condensation of glyceraldehyde with O-methylhydroxylamine.
A diacylglycerol 34:0 in which one acyl group contains 18 carbons the other, 16 carbons
A diacylglycerol 36:0 in which both acyl group contain 18 carbons.
A member of the class of cyclopropanes that is 1-methylidenecyclopropane carrying an additional pent-4-en-1-yl substituent at position 2.
A tertiary amino compound that is ethanolamine in which the two amino hydrogens have been replaced by ethyl and 2-chloroethyl groups.
A member of the class of phenols carrying two tert-butyl substituents at positions 2 and 6.
A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a 2-ethoxyethoxy group.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the two phosphatidyl acyl groups each contain 20 carbons and 5 double bonds.
A member of the class of pyrrolidines in which the only substituent is a methoxymethyl group at position 2 (the S-enantiomer0.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 39 carbons in total with 4 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 39 carbons in total with 5 double bonds.
A beta-alanine derivative that is the amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of beta-alanine with the primary amino group of histamine.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 39 carbons in total with 6 double bonds.
A monocarboxylic acid that is phenylacetic acid carrying two hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 5 on the benzene ring.
A 2-arylpropionic acid that is 2-phenylpropionic acid carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 3 on the benzene ring.
An alkylbenzene that is 1-isopentylbenzene carrying four additional methyl substituents at position 2, 3, 4 and 6.
A medium-chain fatty acid that is hexanoic acid substituted at position 5 by a hydroxy group.
An L-methionine derivative that is the ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of L-methionine with ethanol.
An N-acetyl-L-amino acid derived from L-phosphinothricin.
Any organic heterotricyclic compound with a skeleton consisting of a pyrrole ring ortho-fused at any position to a benzodiazepine bicyclic system.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 28 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 35 carbons in total with 3 double bonds.
